{"title_page": "Mr Eazi", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Mr Eazi\n| background       = solo_singer\n| image            = Mr Eazi.png\n| landscape        = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = A capture from Mr Eazi's 2016 video interview with NdaniTV\n| birth_name       = Oluwatosin Ajibade\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1991|07|19|df=y}}\n| birth_place      = [[Port Harcourt]], [[Rivers State]], Nigeria\n| origin           = Nigerian\n| genre            = {{flatlist|\n*[[Afrobeats#Banku Music|Banku Music]]\n*[[Afrobeats]]}}\n| occupation       = {{flatlist|\n*Singer\n*songwriter\n*entrepreneur}}\n| years_active     = {{nowrap|2012\u2013present}}\n| label            = {{flatlist|\n*[[Mad Decent]]\n*[[Universal Music Group|Universal]] }}\n| associated_acts  = {{flatlist|\n*DJ Juls\n*[[Eugy]]\n*[[Diplo]]\n*[[Big Lean]]\n*[[Joeboy]]}}\n| website          = {{URL|http://mreazi.com}}\n| alias            = Don Eazi\n}}\n\n'''Oluwatosin Ajibade''' (born 19 July 1991),<ref>{{cite web|last1=Solanke|first1=Abiola|title='I'll be working with Wizkid on \"Skin tight\" remix' singer says on Beats 1|url=https://www.pulse.ng/mr-eazi-ill-be-working-with-wizkid-on-skin-tight-remix-singer-says-on-beats-1/xl7gvm0|publisher=Pulse|accessdate=16 August 2019|date=17 November 2016}}</ref> better known by his stage name '''Mr Eazi''', is a Nigerian singer, songwriter, and entrepreneur.<ref name=\"The Guardian Life\">{{cite web|last1=Muoka|first1=Chidera|title=Mr Eazi \u2013 The New Sound of Africa|url=http://life.guardian.ng/2016/09/mr-eazi-the-new-sound-of-africa/|publisher=The Guardian Life|accessdate=22 March 2017|date=4 September 2016}}</ref> He is the pioneer of Banku music, a fusion sound he describes as a mixture of Ghanaian [[highlife]] and Nigerian chord progressions and patterns.<ref name=\"Complex\">{{cite magazine|last1=Kenner|first1=Rob|title=Introducing Mr Eazi, the OVO and Wizkid Favorite Bringing Afrobeats to the Masses|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2017/02/mr-eazi-talks-wizkid-and-ovo-connections-and-afrobeats|magazine=Complex|accessdate=22 March 2017|date=13 February 2017}}</ref> Mr Eazi relocated to [[Kumasi]] in 2008 and enrolled at [[Kwame Nkrumah University of Science and Technology|KNUST]], where he began booking artists to perform at college parties.<ref name=\"The Fader 21\">{{cite magazine|author1=Phiona Okumu|title=Mr Eazi Is West Africa\u2019s Newest Superstar|url=http://www.thefader.com/2017/04/26/mr-eazi-interview-accra-to-lagos-money|magazine=The Fader|date=26 April 2017}}</ref> He showed interest in music after recording a guest verse on \"My Life\", a song that gained traction and became a popular record at KNUST.<ref name=\"Noisey\">{{cite web|last1=Burney|first1=Lawrence|title=Mr. Eazi Wants to Connect a Billion People Through Afrobeats|url=https://noisey.vice.com/en_us/article/mr-eazi-wants-to-connect-a-billon-people-through-afrobeats|publisher=Noisey|accessdate=22 March 2017|date=9 November 2016}}</ref> Mr Eazi released his debut mixtape ''About to Blow'' in July 2013.<ref name=\"Jaguda1\">{{cite web|last1=Jaguda|first1=Ayo|title=Mr Eazi Presents About To Blow \"The Mixtape\"|url=http://jaguda.com/2013/07/21/mr-eazi-presents-about-to-blow-the-mixtape-listen-to-kafaya-i-no-fit-lie/|publisher=Jaguda|accessdate=12 April 2017|date=21 July 2014}}</ref> He gained an international audience following the release of the [[Efya]]-assisted single \"Skin Tight\".<ref name=\"Noiseyy\"/> His second mixtape ''Life Is Eazi, Vol. 1 \u2013 Accra To Lagos'' was released on 10 February 2017.<ref name=\"Pulse 11\">{{cite web|last1=Solanke|first1=Abiola|title=Singer's \"Life Is Eazi Vol. 1 - Accra To Lagos\" mixtape is out now|url=http://pulse.ng/buzz/mr-eazi-singers-life-is-eazi-vol-1-accra-to-lagos-mixtape-is-out-now-id6199452.html|publisher=Pulse Nigeria|accessdate=30 March 2017|date=10 February 2017}}</ref> In March 2018, several outlets reported that Mr Eazi signed a record deal with Diplo's label [[Mad Decent]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Masiyiwa|first1=Sarah|title=Mr Eazi Has Been Signed to Diplo's Record Label|url=http://www.okayafrica.com/mr-eazi-diplo-record-label/|publisher=OkayAfrica|date=28 March 2018}}</ref> Mr Eazi signed a licensing deal with Universal Africa, a subsidiary of [[Universal Music Group]].<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Mr Eazi\u2019s label signs licensing deal with Universal Africa|url=http://thenationonlineng.net/mr-eazis-label-signs-licensing-deal-with-universal-africa/|magazine=The Nation|date=16 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Music career==\n===Early life and career beginnings===\nMr Eazi was born in [[Port Harcourt]], the capital and largest city in [[Rivers State]], Nigeria.<ref name=\"Noisey\"/> He grew up in an entrepreneurial home. His mother owned a small business and his father is a pilot. The latter parent established his own private aviation consulting practice.<ref name=\"Noisey\"/> While attending primary school in Lagos, Mr Eazi had a brief stint in the school's choir.<ref name=\"Noisey\"/> During his upbringing, he listened to records his dad would play for the family while having breakfast.<ref name=\"Highsnobiety\">{{cite web|last1=Smith-Strickland|first1=Stephanie|title=Meet Mr Eazi, the Nigerian Afrobeats Artist Making Global Waves|url=http://www.highsnobiety.com/2017/04/04/mr-eazi-afrobeat-artist/|publisher=Highsnobiety|accessdate=9 April 2017|date=4 April 2017}}</ref> At age 16, Mr Eazi relocated to [[Ghana]] to further his educational endeavors, enrolling in the mechanical engineering program at [[Kwame Nkrumah University of Science and Technology]] (KNUST).<ref name=\"Noisey\"/> Mr Eazi started recording music during his time at KNUST. He contributed guest vocals to the track \"My Life\", a song that gained traction and became a popular record at KNUST. Prior to that, he established a party and promotion company called Swagger Entertainment.<ref name=\"Highsnobiety\"/> He used this platform to book shows and promote events on the campus of KNUST.<ref name=\"Noisey\"/> When he was 23 years old, he returned to Nigeria and opened his own e-commerce platform.<ref name=\"Noisey\"/> Mr Eazi told ''[[The Guardian (Nigeria)|The Guardian]]'' newspaper he briefly worked for [[Schlumberger]] when he returned to Nigeria.<ref name=\"The Guardian Life\"/> He also told the aforementioned newspaper his business ventures included soft drinks import, gold mining, and food distribution.<ref name=\"The Guardian Life\"/> Moreover, he told Highsnobiety he started about six business ventures.<ref name=\"Highsnobiety\"/> In 2014, Mr Eazi quit being a club promoter after an artist failed to show up for the largest party he attempted to throw.<ref name=\"Highsnobiety\"/>\n\n===2013\u20132015: ''About to Blow'' and other releases===\nMr Eazi released his 13-track debut mixtape ''About to Blow'' in July 2013.<ref name=\"Jaguda1\"/> It produced two singles: \"Pipi Dance\" and \"Bankulize\". The former was released in mid-2012, while the latter was released in 2013.<ref name=\"Jaguda1\"/> Mr Eazi recorded the mixtape with producer Klu and released it within a week.<ref name=\"The Fader 21\"/> ''[[The Fader]]'' magazine descrie mixtape as a \"heavily dancehall-leaning SoundCloud playlist\". Prior to releasing the mixtape, Mr Eazi worked with producers such as Magnom, Peeweezle, Nshona, Klumonsta, [[D'Tunes]], and E-Kelly. Moreover, he was featured on Stay Jay's \"Baby Lace\" and Lousika's \"Knockout\".<ref name=\"Jaguda1\"/> In 2014, Mr Eazi relocated to Nigeria. He was contacted by UK-based Ghanaian producer Juls, who got a hold of some of his recordings.<ref name=\"Noisey\"/> Due to not being able to locate the audio files of his old recordings, Mr Eazi's attempt at working with Juls stalled for a long time.<ref name=\"Noisey\"/> Mr Eazi eventually retrieved his audio files and sent them to Juls, who made a new beat and created the artwork for the mixtape's second single \"Bankulize\".<ref name=\"Noisey\"/> The song features vocals from Ghanaian hiplife artist [[Pappy Kojo]] and was released in November 2014.<ref name=\"Noisey\"/> The official remix of \"Bankulize\" features [[Burna Boy]] and was released in September 2016.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mr Eazi \u2013 Bankulize Remix Ft. Burna Boy (Prod. Juls)|url=http://notjustok.com/2016/09/19/mr-eazi-bankulize-remix-ft-burna-boy-prod-juls/|publisher=NotJustOk|accessdate=13 April 2017|date=19 September 2016}}</ref> Mr Eazi premiered the remix on [[Ebro Darden]]'s [[Beats 1]] radio show a month earlier.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mr Eazi ft. Burna Boy \u2013 Bankulize (Remix)|url=http://notjustok.com/2016/08/23/mr-eazi-ft-burna-boy-bankulize-remix/|publisher=NotJustOk|accessdate=13 April 2017|date=23 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2015, Mr Eazi released the dancehall-influenced track \"Skin Tight\". It features guest vocals from Ghanaian singer [[Efya]] and was produced by DJ Juls.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mr. Eazi x Juls ft. Efya \u2013 Skin Tight|url=http://notjustok.com/2015/09/10/mr-eazi-x-juls-ft-efya-skin-tight/|publisher=NotJustOK|accessdate=13 April 2017|date=10 September 2015}}</ref> In an interview with ''[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]'' magazine, Mr Eazi described the song as a \"fusion\".<ref name=\"Complex\"/> He said he spoke Ghanaian pidgin on the delivery and used Nigerian melodies.<ref name=\"Complex\"/> In August 2016, Nigerian record producer [[Cobhams Asuquo]] released a rendition of the song. [[DJ Caise]] released a house remix of the song in September 2016, while [[Terry G]] collaborated with Mr Eazi to release a remix of the song.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Boye|first1=Don|title=DJ Caise \u2013 Skin Tight (House Remix)|url=http://notjustok.com/2016/09/16/dj-caise-skin-tight-house-remix/|publisher=NotJustOk|accessdate=13 April 2017|date=16 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Mr Eazi ft. Terry G \u2013 Skin Tight (Remix)|url=http://notjustok.com/2016/10/07/mr-eazi-ft-terry-g-skin-tight-remix/|publisher=NotJustOk|accessdate=13 April 2017|date=7 October 2016}}</ref> In April 2017, \"Skin Tight\" was featured in an ad for the vodka brand [[Ciroc]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Ghana: Mr. Eazi's Song Featured in New Ad for Diddy's Ciroc|url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201704110597.html|publisher=Ghana Star|date=11 April 2017}}</ref> Mr Eazi was featured on Eugy's 2016 hit single \"Dance for Me\". ''[[The Guardian]]'' newspaper included the song on its list of the 10 biggest African tracks of 2016.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Egbejule|first1=Eromo|title=10 of the biggest African tracks of 2016: Tekno, Babe Wodumo and more|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2016/dec/21/african-tracks-2016-tekno-babe-wodumo-mr-eazi|publisher=The Guadian|accessdate=14 April 2017|date=21 December 2016}}</ref> The music video for \"Dance for Me\" was directed by Vertex and Gabriella Kingsely.<ref name=\"Clash\">{{cite web|title=Eugy x Mr Eazi - 'Dance For Me'|url=http://www.clashmusic.com/videos/eugy-x-mr-eazi-dance-for-me|publisher=Clash|accessdate=14 April 2017|date=9 August 2016}}</ref> Robin Murray of ''Clash'' magazine described the song as a \"salute to their joint Ghanaian heritage\".<ref name=\"Clash\"/> On 17 June 2016, Mr Eazi released the R&B-inspired \"Anointing\", a song that features rap vocals from Ghanaian rapper [[Sarkodie (rapper)|Sarkodie]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Solanke|first1=Abiola|title=Mr Eazi - 'Anointing' ft Sarkodie|url=http://pulse.ng/new_music/new-music-mr-eazi-anointing-ft-sarkodie-id5161116.html|publisher=Pulse|accessdate=17 June 2016}}</ref> Mr Eazi first announced plans for the song in May 2016.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Asante|first1=Samuel|title=Ghana: Mr Eazi Announces New Single \"Anointing\" Featuring Sarkodie|url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201605310507.html|publisher=allAfrica|accessdate=14 April 2017|date=30 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n===2016\u20132017: GMA snub, Twitter backlash, ''Accra to Lagos'', and record deal===\nIn February 2016, organizers of the Vodafone-sponsored [[Ghana Music Awards]] made a decision not to nominate Mr Eazi in any of its Ghanaian-only categories.<ref name=\"Pulse Ghana\">{{cite web|last1=Mawuli|first1=David|title=2016 VGMA nominations list is an insult to artistry|url=http://pulse.com.gh/music/feature-2016-vgma-nominations-list-is-an-insult-to-artistry-id4752487.html|publisher=Pulse|accessdate=11 April 2017|date=5 March 2016}}</ref> According to George Quaye, a spokesperson for Charterhouse, Mr Eazi was disqualified because of his nationality.<ref name=\"Pulse Ghana\"/> Quaye also stated that Mr Eazi was only eligible to compete in the African Artiste of the Year category.<ref name=\"GhanaWeb\"/> However, he failed to pick up a nomination in the aforementioned category because the organizers felt that he isn't as big as the other nominees.<ref name=\"GhanaWeb\">{{cite web|title=VGMA 2016: 'Mr Eazi was disqualified because he's not Ghanaian'|url=http://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/entertainment/VGMA-2016-Mr-Eazi-was-disqualified-because-he-s-not-Ghanaian-420238|publisher=Ghana Web|date=2 March 2016}}</ref> On 11 January 2017, Mr Eazi tweeted that Ghanaian music has a great influence over present-day Nigerian music.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Fayyad|first1=Sara|title=Social media's grand finale of Obama-Biden \"bromance\", Afro-pop star Mr Eazi takes some hard hits, and Egypt trolls \"first single mother\"|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/blogs-trending-38603345|publisher=BBC|date=13 January 2017}}</ref> He received heavy backlash after posting the tweet and trended nationwide in both Ghana and Nigeria. On 12 January 2017, Mr Eazi apologized to Nigerians for the comments that he made.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Augoye|first1=Jayne|title=Mr Eazi apologises to Nigerians after Twitter backlash|url=http://www.premiumtimesng.com/arts-entertainment/music/220311-mr-eazi-apologises-nigerians-twitter-backlash.html|newspaper=Premium Times|accessdate=12 April 2017|date=12 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nFollowing his performance at the [[2016 Ghana Music Awards]], Wizkid announced that he signed Mr Eazi to his imprint Starboy Entertainment.<ref>{{cite news|title=Wizkid signs top Ghanaian singers to StarBoy Worldwide|url=http://www.premiumtimesng.com/arts-entertainment/music/203087-wizkid-signs-top-ghanaian-singers-starboy-worldwide.html|newspaper=Premium Times|accessdate=8 May 2016|date=8 May 2016}}</ref>  However, Mr Eazi told Star FM Ghana in July 2017 that he is not officially signed to Starboy. He also told Star FM Ghana that he is only in business with the imprint.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Brown|first1=Marcus|title=Wizkid Never Signed Me To His Starboy Worldwide Label \u2013 Mr Eazi|url=http://tooxclusive.com/news/wizkid-never-signed-starboy-worldwide-label-mr-eazi/|publisher=TooXlcusive|accessdate=18 April 2018|date=16 July 2017}}</ref> Mr Eazi's second mixtape, ''Life Is Eazi, Vol. 1 \u2013 Accra To Lagos'', was released on 10 February 2017.<ref name=\"Pulse 11\"/> The mixtape was initially scheduled for release on 11 February 2017.<ref name=\"Pulse 11\"/> It debuted at number 4 on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' World Albums chart.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mr Eazi\u2019s \"Accra To Lagos\" Debuts On World Bill Board|url=http://www.thetidenewsonline.com/2017/03/03/mr-eazis-accra-to-lagos-debuts-on-world-bill-board/|publisher=The Tide|accessdate=31 March 2017|date=3 March 2017}}</ref> The mixtape comprises 14 tracks, including three bonus tracks. Guest artists featured on the mixtape include [[Tekno Miles|Tekno]], [[Olamide]], [[Phyno]], Mugeez, Medikal, [[DJ Cuppy]], [[Falz]], and [[Big Lean]]. Its production was handled by [[Maleek Berry]], [[Masterkraft (producer)|Masterkraft]], [[Legendury Beatz]], and [[Young John (producer)|Young John]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kpade|first1=Sabo|title=Mr Eazi Connects Ghana & Nigeria Like No One Else In \u2018Life Is Eazi\u2019|url=http://www.okayafrica.com/audio/mr-eazi-life-is-eazi-download-accra-to-lagos/|publisher=[[OkayAfrica]]|accessdate=31 March 2017}}</ref> Mr Eazi announced on Instagram that the mixtape sold 200,000 copies in pre-orders.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Salihu|first1=Idoko|title=Mr Eazi announces release date for \"Accra to Lagos\" EP|url=http://www.premiumtimesng.com/arts-entertainment/music/221777-mr-eazi-announces-release-date-for-accra-to-lagos-ep.html|newspaper=Premium Times|accessdate=31 March 2017|date=27 January 2017}}</ref> While speaking to [[Julie Adenuga]] on her Beats 1 radio show, he said the mixtape is a tribute to the two cities that influenced the evolution of his sound.<ref>{{cite web|title=MR. EAZI TALKS INSPIRATION BEHIND \u2018ACCRA TO LAGOS\u2019 MIXTAPE ON APPLE\u2019S BEATS1 RADIO|url=http://thenativemag.com/music/can-now-cop-mr-eazis-accra-lagos-mixtape/|publisher=The Native|date=10 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe mixtape's lead single \"Leg Over\" was produced by E-Kelly and released on 2 December 2016. The music video for \"Leg Over\" features cameo appearances from comedian [[Eddie Kadi]], [[Maleek Berry]], and Wizkid. Mr Eazi told Lawrence Burney from Noisey.com that the song is about being taken advantage of in a relationship.<ref name=\"Noiseyy\">{{cite web|last1=Burney|first1=Lawrence|title=Watch Mr. Eazi Confess His Love in His \"Leg Over\" Video|url=https://noisey.vice.com/en_us/article/watch-mr-eazi-confess-his-love-in-his-leg-over-video|publisher=Noisey|accessdate=9 April 2017|date=10 February 2017}}</ref> He also said the song was leaked and wasn't meant to be a single.<ref name=\"Noiseyy\"/> Upon its release in December 2016, \"Leg Over\" inspired numerous dance videos.<ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Dandrige-Lemco|first1=Ben|title=Watch Mr Eazi\u2019s \"Leg Over\" Video Featuring Wizkid And Maleek Berry|url=http://www.thefader.com/2017/02/10/mr-eazi-leg-over-video-wizkid-accra-to-lagos|magazine=The Fader|accessdate=9 April 2017|date=10 February 2017}}</ref> Gabriel Myers Hansen, a critic and editor whose review was posted on the ''Music In Africa'' website, described the song as \"gentle and minimalist\". Hansen also said it is \"freshened by delicate string and percussion placements reminiscent of highlife from decades ago\".<ref>{{cite web|author1=Gabriel Myers Hansen|title=Mr Eazi \u2014 Leg Over|url=http://musicinafrica.net/mr-eazi-%E2%80%94-leg-over|publisher=Music In Africa|accessdate=9 April 2017|date=15 December 2016}}</ref> On 1 February 2017, Mr Eazi released \"Tilapia\" as the mixtape's second single. It features vocals from Ghanaian hip hop artist Medikal.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Akarefa|first1=Jasper|title=Mr Eazi \u2013 Tilapia feat. Medikal (Prod. by Del B)|url=http://dailypost.ng/music/2017/02/01/mr-eazi-tilapia-feat-medikal-prod-del-b/|newspaper=Daily Post|date=1 February 2017}}</ref> On 1 March 2017, Mr Eazi released the [[Sesan Ogunro|Sesan]]-directed music video for \"[[In The Morning (Mr Eazi song)|In The Morning]]\". The song features vocals from Toronto rapper [[Big Lean]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Efe|first1=Jasper|title=Mr Eazi \u2013 In The Morning feat. Big Lean (Dir. by Sesan)|url=http://dailypost.ng/music/2017/03/06/mr-eazi-morning-feat-big-lean-dir-sesan/|newspaper=Daily Post|accessdate=14 April 2017|date=6 March 2017}}</ref> On 1 April 2017, Mr Eazi released the Teekay-directed music video for \"Fight\", a song that features additional vocals from DJ Cuppy.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Solanke|first1=Abiola|title='Fight' ft Cuppy [Video]|url=http://pulse.ng/music_videos/video-mr-eazi-feat-dj-cuppy-fight-id6471625.html|publisher=Pulse|accessdate=9 April 2017|date=3 April 2017}}</ref> On 7 April 2017, Mr Eazi released the music video for \"Business\", a song that features vocals from Mugeez of [[R2Bees]].<ref>{{cite web|title=VIDEO: Mr. Eazi \u2013 Business Ft. Mugeez|url=http://notjustok.com/2017/04/07/video-mr-eazi-business-ft-mugeez/|publisher=NotJustOk|accessdate=9 April 2017|date=7 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n===2019: Coachella and Empawa Africa===\nIn January 2019, it was announced that Mr Eazi will be performing at the 2019 [[Coachella Valley Music and Arts Festival]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vanguardngr.com/2019/01/burna-boy-mr-eazi-to-make-coachella-debut/|title=Burna Boy, Mr Eazi to make Coachella debut|last=adekunle|date=2019-01-03|website=Vanguard News Nigeria|language=en-US|access-date=2019-01-03}}</ref> In August 2019, Mr Eazi launched emPawa Africa, a talent incubation initiative designed to nurture and support up-and-coming African artists. Thirty musicians would be enrolled in the first edition and would receive grant and mentorship to scale up their music career. The initiative is also supported by [[YouTube Music]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbesafrica.com/arts/2019/08/21/mr-eazi-on-a-global-campaign-to-mentor-and-funding-african-artists/|title=Mr Eazi On A Global Campaign To Mentor And Fund African Artists|last=Mwendera|first=Karen|date=2019-08-21|website=Forbes Africa|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-21}}</ref>\n\n==Artistry==\nMr Eazi is known for pioneering [[Afrobeats#Banku Music|Banku music]], a sound \"characterized by percolating rhythms and laid-back vocal delivered in [[Ghanaian Pidgin English]]\".<ref name=\"Complex\"/> Mr Eazi's music largely fits into the category of [[Afrobeats]], a contemporary West African pop genre that marries global pop, [[highlife]], and [[Hip hop music|hip-hop]].<ref name=\"Complex\"/> Mr Eazi's music has been described as having an R&B-like quality reminiscent of artists such as [[Beres Hammond]] and [[Gregory Isaacs]].<ref name=\"Noisey\"/> Lawrence Burney from Noisey.com stated that Mr Eazi uses his deep voice to \"give ballad-like qualities to dance-forward production\".<ref name=\"Noisey\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\nMr Eazi is known to be dating Temi Otedola, daughter of Nigerian billionaire [[Femi Otedola]] and sister to [[DJ Cuppy]].<ref>[https://www.pulse.ng/entertainment/celebrities/mr-eazi-singer-celebrates-girlfriend-temi-otedola-on-her-birthday/97w90pw Singer celebrates girlfriend, Temi Otedola on her birthday]</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n===Mixtapes===\n*''About to Blow'' (2013)\n*''Life is Eazi, Vol. 1 - Accra to Lagos'' (2017)\n*''Life is Eazi, Vol. 2 - Lagos to London'' (2018)\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Event\n!Prize\n!Recipient\n!Result\n!Ref\n|-\n|2018\n|[[The Headies 2018|The Headies]]\n|[[The Headies Award for Hip Hop World Revelation of the Year|Hip Hop World Revelation of the Year]]\n|Himself\n|{{nom}}\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|2017\n|[[MOBO Awards]]\n|Best African Act\n|Himself\n|{{nom}}\n|<ref>{{cite web |title=2017 MOBO AWARDS NOMINATIONS: GET THE FULL LIST NOW |url=https://beta.mobo.com/nominees |publisher=MOBO |accessdate=21 March 2019 |date=16 October 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Nigeria Entertainment Awards]]\n|Afropop Male Artist\n|Himself\n|{{nom}}\n|<ref>{{cite web |title=NIGERIA ENTERTAINMENT AWARDS 2017 FULL NOMINEES LIST |url=https://acceleratetv.com/nigeria-entertainment-awards-2017-full-nominees-list/ |accessdate=21 March 2019 |date=22 August 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=\"8\"|2016\n|[[WatsUp TV Africa Music Video Awards]]\n|Special Recognition Award Music Video Africa \n|\"Skin Tight\" <br/><span style=\"font-size:85%;\">(featuring [[Efya]])</span> \n|{{won}}\n|<ref>{{cite web|last1=Junia|first1=Pep|title=Shatta Wale, Mr Eazi win at WatsUp TV Africa Music Video Awards + FULL LIST|url=https://enewsgh.com/2016/12/28/shatta-wale-mr-eazi-win-watsup-tv-africa-music-video-awards-full-list/|publisher=ENews Ghana|accessdate=14 April 2017|date=28 December 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|[[Soundcity MVP Awards Festival|Soundcity MVP Awards]]\n|Best New Artiste\n|Himself\n|{{won}}\n|rowspan=\"4\"|<ref>{{cite web|last1=Johnson|first1=Ayodele|title=See full list of winners|url=http://pulse.ng/buzz/soundcity-mvp-awards-2016-see-full-list-of-winners-id5968899.html|publisher=Pulse|accessdate=14 April 2017|date=29 December 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n|Song of the Year\n|rowspan=\"2\"|\"Hollup\" <br/><span style=\"font-size:85%;\">(featuring [[Joey B]] and [[Dammy Krane]])</span> \n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|Viewers Choice\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|Listeners Choice\n|\"Skin Tight\" <br/><span style=\"font-size:85%;\">(featuring [[Efya]])</span> \n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|[[The Headies]]\n|[[The Headies Award for Next Rated|Next Rated]]\n|rowspan=\"3\"|Himself\n|{{won}}\n|<ref>{{cite web|title=Full list of Headies 2016 winners|url=http://www.vanguardngr.com/2016/12/full-list-headies-2016-winners/|publisher=Vanguard|accessdate=14 April 2017|date=23 December 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n|MOBO Awards\n|Best African Act\n|{{nom}}\n|<ref>{{cite web|last1=Nankervis|first1=Troy|title=MOBO Awards 2016: Craig David lands two nominations for Best Male Act and Best Song|url=http://metro.co.uk/2016/09/21/mobo-awards-2016-craig-david-lands-two-nominations-for-best-male-act-and-best-song-6142379/|publisher=Metro|date=21 September 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n|Nigeria Entertainment Awards\n|Most Promising Act to Watch\n|{{won}}\n|<ref>{{cite web|last1=Nankervis|first1=Troy|title=NEA 2016: NEA Awards 2016 Full List of Winners|url=http://naijalyricszone.com/nea-awards-2016-full-list-of-winners//|publisher=Naijalyricszone|date=21 September 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://mreazi.com/}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Eazi, Mr}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1991 births]]\n[[Category:Nigerian singers]]\n[[Category:Nigerian male singers]]\n[[Category:Singers from Port Harcourt]]\n[[Category:Yoruba musicians]]\n[[Category:Kwame Nkrumah University of Science and Technology alumni]]\n[[Category:21st-century Nigerian musicians]]\n[[Category:English-language singers from Nigeria]]\n[[Category:Nigerian businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Yoruba businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Rivers State]]\n[[Category:Mad Decent artists]]\n[[Category:21st-century Nigerian singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century male singers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Mr Eazi\n| background       = solo_singer\n| image            = Mr Eazi.png\n| landscape        = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = A capture from Mr Eazi's 2016 video interview with NdaniTV\n| birth_name       = Oluwatosin Ajibade\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1991|07|19|df=y}}\n| birth_place      = [[Port Harcourt]], [[Rivers State]], Nigeria\n| origin           = <!-- The origin field is intended for musical origin, not biological origin. Please refrained from adding Lagos, Nigeria, or the place his parents are from. -->[[Kumasi]], Ghana<!-- The origin field is intended for musical origin, not biological origin. Please refrained from adding Lagos, Nigeria, or the place his parents are from. -->\n| genre            = {{flatlist|\n*[[Afrobeats#Banku Music|Banku Music]]\n*[[Afrobeats]]}}\n| occupation       = {{flatlist|\n*Singer\n*songwriter\n*entrepreneur}}\n| years_active     = {{nowrap|2012\u2013present}}\n| label            = {{flatlist|\n*[[Mad Decent]]\n*[[Universal Music Group|Universal]] }}\n| associated_acts  = {{flatlist|\n*DJ Juls\n*[[Eugy]]\n*[[Diplo]]\n*[[Big Lean]]\n*[[Joeboy]]}}\n| website          = {{URL|http://mreazi.com}}\n| alias            = Don Eazi\n}}\n\n'''Oluwatosin Ajibade''' (born 19 July 1991),<ref>{{cite web|last1=Solanke|first1=Abiola|title='I'll be working with Wizkid on \"Skin tight\" remix' singer says on Beats 1|url=https://www.pulse.ng/mr-eazi-ill-be-working-with-wizkid-on-skin-tight-remix-singer-says-on-beats-1/xl7gvm0|publisher=Pulse|accessdate=16 August 2019|date=17 November 2016}}</ref> better known by his stage name '''Mr Eazi''', is a Nigerian singer, songwriter, and entrepreneur.<ref name=\"The Guardian Life\">{{cite web|last1=Muoka|first1=Chidera|title=Mr Eazi \u2013 The New Sound of Africa|url=http://life.guardian.ng/2016/09/mr-eazi-the-new-sound-of-africa/|publisher=The Guardian Life|accessdate=22 March 2017|date=4 September 2016}}</ref> He is the pioneer of Banku music, a fusion sound he describes as a mixture of Ghanaian [[highlife]] and Nigerian chord progressions and patterns.<ref name=\"Complex\">{{cite magazine|last1=Kenner|first1=Rob|title=Introducing Mr Eazi, the OVO and Wizkid Favorite Bringing Afrobeats to the Masses|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2017/02/mr-eazi-talks-wizkid-and-ovo-connections-and-afrobeats|magazine=Complex|accessdate=22 March 2017|date=13 February 2017}}</ref> Mr Eazi relocated to [[Kumasi]] in 2008 and enrolled at [[Kwame Nkrumah University of Science and Technology|KNUST]], where he began booking artists to perform at college parties.<ref name=\"The Fader 21\">{{cite magazine|author1=Phiona Okumu|title=Mr Eazi Is West Africa\u2019s Newest Superstar|url=http://www.thefader.com/2017/04/26/mr-eazi-interview-accra-to-lagos-money|magazine=The Fader|date=26 April 2017}}</ref> He showed interest in music after recording a guest verse on \"My Life\", a song that gained traction and became a popular record at KNUST.<ref name=\"Noisey\">{{cite web|last1=Burney|first1=Lawrence|title=Mr. Eazi Wants to Connect a Billion People Through Afrobeats|url=https://noisey.vice.com/en_us/article/mr-eazi-wants-to-connect-a-billon-people-through-afrobeats|publisher=Noisey|accessdate=22 March 2017|date=9 November 2016}}</ref> Mr Eazi released his debut mixtape ''About to Blow'' in July 2013.<ref name=\"Jaguda1\">{{cite web|last1=Jaguda|first1=Ayo|title=Mr Eazi Presents About To Blow \"The Mixtape\"|url=http://jaguda.com/2013/07/21/mr-eazi-presents-about-to-blow-the-mixtape-listen-to-kafaya-i-no-fit-lie/|publisher=Jaguda|accessdate=12 April 2017|date=21 July 2014}}</ref> He gained an international audience following the release of the [[Efya]]-assisted single \"Skin Tight\".<ref name=\"Noiseyy\"/> His second mixtape ''Life Is Eazi, Vol. 1 \u2013 Accra To Lagos'' was released on 10 February 2017.<ref name=\"Pulse 11\">{{cite web|last1=Solanke|first1=Abiola|title=Singer's \"Life Is Eazi Vol. 1 - Accra To Lagos\" mixtape is out now|url=http://pulse.ng/buzz/mr-eazi-singers-life-is-eazi-vol-1-accra-to-lagos-mixtape-is-out-now-id6199452.html|publisher=Pulse Nigeria|accessdate=30 March 2017|date=10 February 2017}}</ref> In March 2018, several outlets reported that Mr Eazi signed a record deal with Diplo's label [[Mad Decent]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Masiyiwa|first1=Sarah|title=Mr Eazi Has Been Signed to Diplo's Record Label|url=http://www.okayafrica.com/mr-eazi-diplo-record-label/|publisher=OkayAfrica|date=28 March 2018}}</ref> Mr Eazi signed a licensing deal with Universal Africa, a subsidiary of [[Universal Music Group]].<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Mr Eazi\u2019s label signs licensing deal with Universal Africa|url=http://thenationonlineng.net/mr-eazis-label-signs-licensing-deal-with-universal-africa/|magazine=The Nation|date=16 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Music career==\n===Early life and career beginnings===\nMr Eazi was born in [[Port Harcourt]], the capital and largest city in [[Rivers State]], Nigeria.<ref name=\"Noisey\"/> He grew up in an entrepreneurial home. His mother owned a small business and his father is a pilot. The latter parent established his own private aviation consulting practice.<ref name=\"Noisey\"/> While attending primary school in Lagos, Mr Eazi had a brief stint in the school's choir.<ref name=\"Noisey\"/> During his upbringing, he listened to records his dad would play for the family while having breakfast.<ref name=\"Highsnobiety\">{{cite web|last1=Smith-Strickland|first1=Stephanie|title=Meet Mr Eazi, the Nigerian Afrobeats Artist Making Global Waves|url=http://www.highsnobiety.com/2017/04/04/mr-eazi-afrobeat-artist/|publisher=Highsnobiety|accessdate=9 April 2017|date=4 April 2017}}</ref> At age 16, Mr Eazi relocated to [[Ghana]] to further his educational endeavors, enrolling in the mechanical engineering program at [[Kwame Nkrumah University of Science and Technology]] (KNUST).<ref name=\"Noisey\"/> Mr Eazi started recording music during his time at KNUST. He contributed guest vocals to the track \"My Life\", a song that gained traction and became a popular record at KNUST. Prior to that, he established a party and promotion company called Swagger Entertainment.<ref name=\"Highsnobiety\"/> He used this platform to book shows and promote events on the campus of KNUST.<ref name=\"Noisey\"/> When he was 23 years old, he returned to Nigeria and opened his own e-commerce platform.<ref name=\"Noisey\"/> Mr Eazi told ''[[The Guardian (Nigeria)|The Guardian]]'' newspaper he briefly worked for [[Schlumberger]] when he returned to Nigeria.<ref name=\"The Guardian Life\"/> He also told the aforementioned newspaper his business ventures included soft drinks import, gold mining, and food distribution.<ref name=\"The Guardian Life\"/> Moreover, he told Highsnobiety he started about six business ventures.<ref name=\"Highsnobiety\"/> In 2014, Mr Eazi quit being a club promoter after an artist failed to show up for the largest party he attempted to throw.<ref name=\"Highsnobiety\"/>\n\n===2013\u20132015: ''About to Blow'' and other releases===\nMr Eazi released his 13-track debut mixtape ''About to Blow'' in July 2013.<ref name=\"Jaguda1\"/> It produced two singles: \"Pipi Dance\" and \"Bankulize\". The former was released in mid-2012, while the latter was released in 2013.<ref name=\"Jaguda1\"/> Mr Eazi recorded the mixtape with producer Klu and released it within a week.<ref name=\"The Fader 21\"/> ''[[The Fader]]'' magazine descrie mixtape as a \"heavily dancehall-leaning SoundCloud playlist\". Prior to releasing the mixtape, Mr Eazi worked with producers such as Magnom, Peeweezle, Nshona, Klumonsta, [[D'Tunes]], and E-Kelly. Moreover, he was featured on Stay Jay's \"Baby Lace\" and Lousika's \"Knockout\".<ref name=\"Jaguda1\"/> In 2014, Mr Eazi relocated to Nigeria. He was contacted by UK-based Ghanaian producer Juls, who got a hold of some of his recordings.<ref name=\"Noisey\"/> Due to not being able to locate the audio files of his old recordings, Mr Eazi's attempt at working with Juls stalled for a long time.<ref name=\"Noisey\"/> Mr Eazi eventually retrieved his audio files and sent them to Juls, who made a new beat and created the artwork for the mixtape's second single \"Bankulize\".<ref name=\"Noisey\"/> The song features vocals from Ghanaian hiplife artist [[Pappy Kojo]] and was released in November 2014.<ref name=\"Noisey\"/> The official remix of \"Bankulize\" features [[Burna Boy]] and was released in September 2016.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mr Eazi \u2013 Bankulize Remix Ft. Burna Boy (Prod. Juls)|url=http://notjustok.com/2016/09/19/mr-eazi-bankulize-remix-ft-burna-boy-prod-juls/|publisher=NotJustOk|accessdate=13 April 2017|date=19 September 2016}}</ref> Mr Eazi premiered the remix on [[Ebro Darden]]'s [[Beats 1]] radio show a month earlier.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mr Eazi ft. Burna Boy \u2013 Bankulize (Remix)|url=http://notjustok.com/2016/08/23/mr-eazi-ft-burna-boy-bankulize-remix/|publisher=NotJustOk|accessdate=13 April 2017|date=23 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2015, Mr Eazi released the dancehall-influenced track \"Skin Tight\". It features guest vocals from Ghanaian singer [[Efya]] and was produced by DJ Juls.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mr. Eazi x Juls ft. Efya \u2013 Skin Tight|url=http://notjustok.com/2015/09/10/mr-eazi-x-juls-ft-efya-skin-tight/|publisher=NotJustOK|accessdate=13 April 2017|date=10 September 2015}}</ref> In an interview with ''[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]'' magazine, Mr Eazi described the song as a \"fusion\".<ref name=\"Complex\"/> He said he spoke Ghanaian pidgin on the delivery and used Nigerian melodies.<ref name=\"Complex\"/> In August 2016, Nigerian record producer [[Cobhams Asuquo]] released a rendition of the song. [[DJ Caise]] released a house remix of the song in September 2016, while [[Terry G]] collaborated with Mr Eazi to release a remix of the song.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Boye|first1=Don|title=DJ Caise \u2013 Skin Tight (House Remix)|url=http://notjustok.com/2016/09/16/dj-caise-skin-tight-house-remix/|publisher=NotJustOk|accessdate=13 April 2017|date=16 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Mr Eazi ft. Terry G \u2013 Skin Tight (Remix)|url=http://notjustok.com/2016/10/07/mr-eazi-ft-terry-g-skin-tight-remix/|publisher=NotJustOk|accessdate=13 April 2017|date=7 October 2016}}</ref> In April 2017, \"Skin Tight\" was featured in an ad for the vodka brand [[Ciroc]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Ghana: Mr. Eazi's Song Featured in New Ad for Diddy's Ciroc|url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201704110597.html|publisher=Ghana Star|date=11 April 2017}}</ref> Mr Eazi was featured on Eugy's 2016 hit single \"Dance for Me\". ''[[The Guardian]]'' newspaper included the song on its list of the 10 biggest African tracks of 2016.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Egbejule|first1=Eromo|title=10 of the biggest African tracks of 2016: Tekno, Babe Wodumo and more|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2016/dec/21/african-tracks-2016-tekno-babe-wodumo-mr-eazi|publisher=The Guadian|accessdate=14 April 2017|date=21 December 2016}}</ref> The music video for \"Dance for Me\" was directed by Vertex and Gabriella Kingsely.<ref name=\"Clash\">{{cite web|title=Eugy x Mr Eazi - 'Dance For Me'|url=http://www.clashmusic.com/videos/eugy-x-mr-eazi-dance-for-me|publisher=Clash|accessdate=14 April 2017|date=9 August 2016}}</ref> Robin Murray of ''Clash'' magazine described the song as a \"salute to their joint Ghanaian heritage\".<ref name=\"Clash\"/> On 17 June 2016, Mr Eazi released the R&B-inspired \"Anointing\", a song that features rap vocals from Ghanaian rapper [[Sarkodie (rapper)|Sarkodie]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Solanke|first1=Abiola|title=Mr Eazi - 'Anointing' ft Sarkodie|url=http://pulse.ng/new_music/new-music-mr-eazi-anointing-ft-sarkodie-id5161116.html|publisher=Pulse|accessdate=17 June 2016}}</ref> Mr Eazi first announced plans for the song in May 2016.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Asante|first1=Samuel|title=Ghana: Mr Eazi Announces New Single \"Anointing\" Featuring Sarkodie|url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201605310507.html|publisher=allAfrica|accessdate=14 April 2017|date=30 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n===2016\u20132017: GMA snub, Twitter backlash, ''Accra to Lagos'', and record deal===\nIn February 2016, organizers of the Vodafone-sponsored [[Ghana Music Awards]] made a decision not to nominate Mr Eazi in any of its Ghanaian-only categories.<ref name=\"Pulse Ghana\">{{cite web|last1=Mawuli|first1=David|title=2016 VGMA nominations list is an insult to artistry|url=http://pulse.com.gh/music/feature-2016-vgma-nominations-list-is-an-insult-to-artistry-id4752487.html|publisher=Pulse|accessdate=11 April 2017|date=5 March 2016}}</ref> According to George Quaye, a spokesperson for Charterhouse, Mr Eazi was disqualified because of his nationality.<ref name=\"Pulse Ghana\"/> Quaye also stated that Mr Eazi was only eligible to compete in the African Artiste of the Year category.<ref name=\"GhanaWeb\"/> However, he failed to pick up a nomination in the aforementioned category because the organizers felt that he isn't as big as the other nominees.<ref name=\"GhanaWeb\">{{cite web|title=VGMA 2016: 'Mr Eazi was disqualified because he's not Ghanaian'|url=http://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/entertainment/VGMA-2016-Mr-Eazi-was-disqualified-because-he-s-not-Ghanaian-420238|publisher=Ghana Web|date=2 March 2016}}</ref> On 11 January 2017, Mr Eazi tweeted that Ghanaian music has a great influence over present-day Nigerian music.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Fayyad|first1=Sara|title=Social media's grand finale of Obama-Biden \"bromance\", Afro-pop star Mr Eazi takes some hard hits, and Egypt trolls \"first single mother\"|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/blogs-trending-38603345|publisher=BBC|date=13 January 2017}}</ref> He received heavy backlash after posting the tweet and trended nationwide in both Ghana and Nigeria. On 12 January 2017, Mr Eazi apologized to Nigerians for the comments that he made.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Augoye|first1=Jayne|title=Mr Eazi apologises to Nigerians after Twitter backlash|url=http://www.premiumtimesng.com/arts-entertainment/music/220311-mr-eazi-apologises-nigerians-twitter-backlash.html|newspaper=Premium Times|accessdate=12 April 2017|date=12 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nFollowing his performance at the [[2016 Ghana Music Awards]], Wizkid announced that he signed Mr Eazi to his imprint Starboy Entertainment.<ref>{{cite news|title=Wizkid signs top Ghanaian singers to StarBoy Worldwide|url=http://www.premiumtimesng.com/arts-entertainment/music/203087-wizkid-signs-top-ghanaian-singers-starboy-worldwide.html|newspaper=Premium Times|accessdate=8 May 2016|date=8 May 2016}}</ref>  However, Mr Eazi told Star FM Ghana in July 2017 that he is not officially signed to Starboy. He also told Star FM Ghana that he is only in business with the imprint.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Brown|first1=Marcus|title=Wizkid Never Signed Me To His Starboy Worldwide Label \u2013 Mr Eazi|url=http://tooxclusive.com/news/wizkid-never-signed-starboy-worldwide-label-mr-eazi/|publisher=TooXlcusive|accessdate=18 April 2018|date=16 July 2017}}</ref> Mr Eazi's second mixtape, ''Life Is Eazi, Vol. 1 \u2013 Accra To Lagos'', was released on 10 February 2017.<ref name=\"Pulse 11\"/> The mixtape was initially scheduled for release on 11 February 2017.<ref name=\"Pulse 11\"/> It debuted at number 4 on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' World Albums chart.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mr Eazi\u2019s \"Accra To Lagos\" Debuts On World Bill Board|url=http://www.thetidenewsonline.com/2017/03/03/mr-eazis-accra-to-lagos-debuts-on-world-bill-board/|publisher=The Tide|accessdate=31 March 2017|date=3 March 2017}}</ref> The mixtape comprises 14 tracks, including three bonus tracks. Guest artists featured on the mixtape include [[Tekno Miles|Tekno]], [[Olamide]], [[Phyno]], Mugeez, Medikal, [[DJ Cuppy]], [[Falz]], and [[Big Lean]]. Its production was handled by [[Maleek Berry]], [[Masterkraft (producer)|Masterkraft]], [[Legendury Beatz]], and [[Young John (producer)|Young John]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kpade|first1=Sabo|title=Mr Eazi Connects Ghana & Nigeria Like No One Else In \u2018Life Is Eazi\u2019|url=http://www.okayafrica.com/audio/mr-eazi-life-is-eazi-download-accra-to-lagos/|publisher=[[OkayAfrica]]|accessdate=31 March 2017}}</ref> Mr Eazi announced on Instagram that the mixtape sold 200,000 copies in pre-orders.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Salihu|first1=Idoko|title=Mr Eazi announces release date for \"Accra to Lagos\" EP|url=http://www.premiumtimesng.com/arts-entertainment/music/221777-mr-eazi-announces-release-date-for-accra-to-lagos-ep.html|newspaper=Premium Times|accessdate=31 March 2017|date=27 January 2017}}</ref> While speaking to [[Julie Adenuga]] on her Beats 1 radio show, he said the mixtape is a tribute to the two cities that influenced the evolution of his sound.<ref>{{cite web|title=MR. EAZI TALKS INSPIRATION BEHIND \u2018ACCRA TO LAGOS\u2019 MIXTAPE ON APPLE\u2019S BEATS1 RADIO|url=http://thenativemag.com/music/can-now-cop-mr-eazis-accra-lagos-mixtape/|publisher=The Native|date=10 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe mixtape's lead single \"Leg Over\" was produced by E-Kelly and released on 2 December 2016. The music video for \"Leg Over\" features cameo appearances from comedian [[Eddie Kadi]], [[Maleek Berry]], and Wizkid. Mr Eazi told Lawrence Burney from Noisey.com that the song is about being taken advantage of in a relationship.<ref name=\"Noiseyy\">{{cite web|last1=Burney|first1=Lawrence|title=Watch Mr. Eazi Confess His Love in His \"Leg Over\" Video|url=https://noisey.vice.com/en_us/article/watch-mr-eazi-confess-his-love-in-his-leg-over-video|publisher=Noisey|accessdate=9 April 2017|date=10 February 2017}}</ref> He also said the song was leaked and wasn't meant to be a single.<ref name=\"Noiseyy\"/> Upon its release in December 2016, \"Leg Over\" inspired numerous dance videos.<ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Dandrige-Lemco|first1=Ben|title=Watch Mr Eazi\u2019s \"Leg Over\" Video Featuring Wizkid And Maleek Berry|url=http://www.thefader.com/2017/02/10/mr-eazi-leg-over-video-wizkid-accra-to-lagos|magazine=The Fader|accessdate=9 April 2017|date=10 February 2017}}</ref> Gabriel Myers Hansen, a critic and editor whose review was posted on the ''Music In Africa'' website, described the song as \"gentle and minimalist\". Hansen also said it is \"freshened by delicate string and percussion placements reminiscent of highlife from decades ago\".<ref>{{cite web|author1=Gabriel Myers Hansen|title=Mr Eazi \u2014 Leg Over|url=http://musicinafrica.net/mr-eazi-%E2%80%94-leg-over|publisher=Music In Africa|accessdate=9 April 2017|date=15 December 2016}}</ref> On 1 February 2017, Mr Eazi released \"Tilapia\" as the mixtape's second single. It features vocals from Ghanaian hip hop artist Medikal.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Akarefa|first1=Jasper|title=Mr Eazi \u2013 Tilapia feat. Medikal (Prod. by Del B)|url=http://dailypost.ng/music/2017/02/01/mr-eazi-tilapia-feat-medikal-prod-del-b/|newspaper=Daily Post|date=1 February 2017}}</ref> On 1 March 2017, Mr Eazi released the [[Sesan Ogunro|Sesan]]-directed music video for \"[[In The Morning (Mr Eazi song)|In The Morning]]\". The song features vocals from Toronto rapper [[Big Lean]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Efe|first1=Jasper|title=Mr Eazi \u2013 In The Morning feat. Big Lean (Dir. by Sesan)|url=http://dailypost.ng/music/2017/03/06/mr-eazi-morning-feat-big-lean-dir-sesan/|newspaper=Daily Post|accessdate=14 April 2017|date=6 March 2017}}</ref> On 1 April 2017, Mr Eazi released the Teekay-directed music video for \"Fight\", a song that features additional vocals from DJ Cuppy.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Solanke|first1=Abiola|title='Fight' ft Cuppy [Video]|url=http://pulse.ng/music_videos/video-mr-eazi-feat-dj-cuppy-fight-id6471625.html|publisher=Pulse|accessdate=9 April 2017|date=3 April 2017}}</ref> On 7 April 2017, Mr Eazi released the music video for \"Business\", a song that features vocals from Mugeez of [[R2Bees]].<ref>{{cite web|title=VIDEO: Mr. Eazi \u2013 Business Ft. Mugeez|url=http://notjustok.com/2017/04/07/video-mr-eazi-business-ft-mugeez/|publisher=NotJustOk|accessdate=9 April 2017|date=7 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n===2019: Coachella and Empawa Africa===\nIn January 2019, it was announced that Mr Eazi will be performing at the 2019 [[Coachella Valley Music and Arts Festival]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vanguardngr.com/2019/01/burna-boy-mr-eazi-to-make-coachella-debut/|title=Burna Boy, Mr Eazi to make Coachella debut|last=adekunle|date=2019-01-03|website=Vanguard News Nigeria|language=en-US|access-date=2019-01-03}}</ref> In August 2019, Mr Eazi launched emPawa Africa, a talent incubation initiative designed to nurture and support up-and-coming African artists. Thirty musicians would be enrolled in the first edition and would receive grant and mentorship to scale up their music career. The initiative is also supported by [[YouTube Music]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbesafrica.com/arts/2019/08/21/mr-eazi-on-a-global-campaign-to-mentor-and-funding-african-artists/|title=Mr Eazi On A Global Campaign To Mentor And Fund African Artists|last=Mwendera|first=Karen|date=2019-08-21|website=Forbes Africa|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-21}}</ref>\n\n==Artistry==\nMr Eazi is known for pioneering [[Afrobeats#Banku Music|Banku music]], a sound \"characterized by percolating rhythms and laid-back vocal delivered in [[Ghanaian Pidgin English]]\".<ref name=\"Complex\"/> Mr Eazi's music largely fits into the category of [[Afrobeats]], a contemporary West African pop genre that marries global pop, [[highlife]], and [[Hip hop music|hip-hop]].<ref name=\"Complex\"/> Mr Eazi's music has been described as having an R&B-like quality reminiscent of artists such as [[Beres Hammond]] and [[Gregory Isaacs]].<ref name=\"Noisey\"/> Lawrence Burney from Noisey.com stated that Mr Eazi uses his deep voice to \"give ballad-like qualities to dance-forward production\".<ref name=\"Noisey\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\nMr Eazi is known to be dating Temi Otedola, daughter of Nigerian billionaire [[Femi Otedola]] and sister to [[DJ Cuppy]].<ref>[https://www.pulse.ng/entertainment/celebrities/mr-eazi-singer-celebrates-girlfriend-temi-otedola-on-her-birthday/97w90pw Singer celebrates girlfriend, Temi Otedola on her birthday]</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n===Mixtapes===\n*''About to Blow'' (2013)\n*''Life is Eazi, Vol. 1 - Accra to Lagos'' (2017)\n*''Life is Eazi, Vol. 2 - Lagos to London'' (2018)\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Event\n!Prize\n!Recipient\n!Result\n!Ref\n|-\n|2018\n|[[The Headies 2018|The Headies]]\n|[[The Headies Award for Hip Hop World Revelation of the Year|Hip Hop World Revelation of the Year]]\n|Himself\n|{{nom}}\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|2017\n|[[MOBO Awards]]\n|Best African Act\n|Himself\n|{{nom}}\n|<ref>{{cite web |title=2017 MOBO AWARDS NOMINATIONS: GET THE FULL LIST NOW |url=https://beta.mobo.com/nominees |publisher=MOBO |accessdate=21 March 2019 |date=16 October 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Nigeria Entertainment Awards]]\n|Afropop Male Artist\n|Himself\n|{{nom}}\n|<ref>{{cite web |title=NIGERIA ENTERTAINMENT AWARDS 2017 FULL NOMINEES LIST |url=https://acceleratetv.com/nigeria-entertainment-awards-2017-full-nominees-list/ |accessdate=21 March 2019 |date=22 August 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=\"8\"|2016\n|[[WatsUp TV Africa Music Video Awards]]\n|Special Recognition Award Music Video Africa \n|\"Skin Tight\" <br/><span style=\"font-size:85%;\">(featuring [[Efya]])</span> \n|{{won}}\n|<ref>{{cite web|last1=Junia|first1=Pep|title=Shatta Wale, Mr Eazi win at WatsUp TV Africa Music Video Awards + FULL LIST|url=https://enewsgh.com/2016/12/28/shatta-wale-mr-eazi-win-watsup-tv-africa-music-video-awards-full-list/|publisher=ENews Ghana|accessdate=14 April 2017|date=28 December 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|[[Soundcity MVP Awards Festival|Soundcity MVP Awards]]\n|Best New Artiste\n|Himself\n|{{won}}\n|rowspan=\"4\"|<ref>{{cite web|last1=Johnson|first1=Ayodele|title=See full list of winners|url=http://pulse.ng/buzz/soundcity-mvp-awards-2016-see-full-list-of-winners-id5968899.html|publisher=Pulse|accessdate=14 April 2017|date=29 December 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n|Song of the Year\n|rowspan=\"2\"|\"Hollup\" <br/><span style=\"font-size:85%;\">(featuring [[Joey B]] and [[Dammy Krane]])</span> \n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|Viewers Choice\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|Listeners Choice\n|\"Skin Tight\" <br/><span style=\"font-size:85%;\">(featuring [[Efya]])</span> \n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|[[The Headies]]\n|[[The Headies Award for Next Rated|Next Rated]]\n|rowspan=\"3\"|Himself\n|{{won}}\n|<ref>{{cite web|title=Full list of Headies 2016 winners|url=http://www.vanguardngr.com/2016/12/full-list-headies-2016-winners/|publisher=Vanguard|accessdate=14 April 2017|date=23 December 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n|MOBO Awards\n|Best African Act\n|{{nom}}\n|<ref>{{cite web|last1=Nankervis|first1=Troy|title=MOBO Awards 2016: Craig David lands two nominations for Best Male Act and Best Song|url=http://metro.co.uk/2016/09/21/mobo-awards-2016-craig-david-lands-two-nominations-for-best-male-act-and-best-song-6142379/|publisher=Metro|date=21 September 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n|Nigeria Entertainment Awards\n|Most Promising Act to Watch\n|{{won}}\n|<ref>{{cite web|last1=Nankervis|first1=Troy|title=NEA 2016: NEA Awards 2016 Full List of Winners|url=http://naijalyricszone.com/nea-awards-2016-full-list-of-winners//|publisher=Naijalyricszone|date=21 September 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://mreazi.com/}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Eazi, Mr}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1991 births]]\n[[Category:Nigerian singers]]\n[[Category:Nigerian male singers]]\n[[Category:Singers from Port Harcourt]]\n[[Category:Yoruba musicians]]\n[[Category:Kwame Nkrumah University of Science and Technology alumni]]\n[[Category:21st-century Nigerian musicians]]\n[[Category:English-language singers from Nigeria]]\n[[Category:N